## Findings: `/tmp/qpb_v1211_sonnet_CHI-12`

### middleware/recoverer.go

**Line 24 — BUG, Critical: `http.ErrAbortHandler` swallowed, not re-panicked**

The combined condition `rvr != nil && rvr != http.ErrAbortHandler` causes the entire defer body to be skipped when `rvr == http.ErrAbortHandler` — the panic is consumed without calling `panic(rvr)`. The reference implementation explicitly calls `panic(rvr)` after detecting ErrAbortHandler so net/http can abort the connection. Without this re-panic, chi silently swallows the abort signal, and the server may write additional data on a connection that was intentionally aborted.

**Line 33 — BUG, High: Missing `Connection != "Upgrade"` guard**

`w.WriteHeader(http.StatusInternalServerError)` is called for all panics with no check for `r.Header.Get("Connection") != "Upgrade"`. For WebSocket or other upgraded connections, this injects HTTP framing bytes into an already-upgraded stream, corrupting the WebSocket protocol.

### middleware/realip.go

**Line 43 — BUG, High: No `net.ParseIP()` validation**

Raw header values are set as `r.RemoteAddr` without any IP format check. An attacker controlling `X-Real-IP` or `X-Forwarded-For` can inject arbitrary strings, bypassing all downstream IP-based access control, rate limiting, and audit logging.

**Line 40 — BUG, Medium: `True-Client-IP` header missing; wrong priority order**

The required priority chain is `True-Client-IP > X-Real-IP > X-Forwarded-For` but the code only checks `X-Real-IP` and `X-Forwarded-For`. CDN/proxy environments that set `True-Client-IP` will produce incorrect RemoteAddr values.

### mux.go / context.go / tree.go / timeout.go / throttle.go

No findings — all Focus Area checks pass.
